rliest is worst because it encodes the wrong semantics; median is not ideal for dates and unsupported in guidance for date semantics; prefer_higher_trust is a defensible fallback only if one source consistently formats better, but the probe did not show a dominant exact-match source. Voting best matches cases where multiple sources repeat the same year/date and avoids earliest-date bias. Expect meaningful improvement, though exact ceiling is limited by residual formatting/time-part and source disagreement.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.096\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "assets",\n      "issue": "Source values are in incompatible scales/units (e.g. billions like 162.8 vs absolute amounts like 162800000000), so any fusion-only resolver will remain wrong. Current most_complete cannot repair magnitude mismatches.",\n      "fix": "Do not change in pipeline_adaption. Defer to a later normalization_node pass to standardize assets into the validation format (absolute numeric string/integer, not billions shorthand) before fusion.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Evidence: both dbpedia and forbes have 0% exact/fuzzy against validation for assets, and examples show magnitude conversion errors rather than source-choice errors. voting, trust-based selection, median, maximum, or most_complete would all still pick unnormalized numbers. Therefore this attribute is structurally limited under frozen infrastructure and should not be altered in pipeline_adaption.",\n      "class": "structurally_limited",\n      "expected_impact": 0.0\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "keypeople_name",\n      "issue": "Current most_complete often returns partial lists or nulls, but the attribute is highly sparse (80.8% null) and validation often expects combined lists. However source coverage limits attainable accuracy.",\n      "fix": "Optional low-priority experiment after city/founded: change keypeople_name from most_complete to union if the column is represented as