and what to try next.\n            \n            9. AUTO DIAGNOSTICS FROM THE LAST EXECUTION (summarized):\n            ID alignment: direct=52.0%, mapped=100.0%\n  ⚠ Low direct ID coverage — fused entities may use different ID format than evaluation set\nTop mismatch reasons:\n  - mismatch: 57.4%\n  - missing_fused_value: 42.6%\nFusion size comparison:\n  - blocking estimate: 12004, actual: 12870 (error: 7%)\n    Estimate is close to actual fused size. Blocking estimate was conservative; downstream matching/fusion retained more entities than expected.\n  - matching estimate: 11792, actual: 12870 (error: 9%)\n    Estimate is close to actual fused size. Matching estimate seems conservative; matcher/fusion retained more clusters than projected.\n\n            You MUST react to these diagnostics:\n            - Always set `include_singletons=True`. The goal is the full fused dataset, never matched-only output.\n            - Preserve source IDs for evaluation alignment when mapped ID coverage is low or missing_fused_value is high.\n            - If list-attribute accuracy is very low, do not blindly union noisy lists; use a robust strategy (trusted-source selection or consensus with normalization).\n            - Always write correspondence files for every evaluated pair to `output/runs/20260322_102925_companies/correspondences/` so cluster analysis uses current run artifacts.\n            - When passing correspondences into PyDI fusion, the required schema is `id1`/`id2`. Do not invent alternate required columns such as `id_l`/`id_r`.\n            \n            11. INVESTIGATOR ACTION PLAN (RANKED):\n            [\n  {\n    "action": "Keep city as an attribute-specific fusion rule in pipeline_adaption, but use prefer_higher_trust with trust_map={\'fullcontact\': 3, \'dbpedia\': 2, \'forbes\': 1} and preserve MaximumBipartiteMatching post-clustering.",\n    "target_attributes": [\n      "city"\n    ],\n    "priority_score": 0.12,\n    "confidence": 0.8,\n    "source": 